class Solution:
    def maxRotateFunction(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:
        n = len(nums)
        if n == 0:
            return 0
        S = sum(nums)
        cur = sum(i * nums[i] for i in range(n))
        max_val = cur
        for k in range(1, n):
            cur = cur + S - n * nums[n - k]
            max_val = max(max_val, cur)
        return max_val

"""
Approach & Reasoning:
Compute F(0) = sum(i * nums[i] for i in range(n)) and the total sum S = sum(nums).

When rotating the array clockwise by one position, the new F value satisfies the recurrence:
F(k+1) = F(k) + S - n * nums[n-k]

This holds because:
- Every element's multiplier increases by 1, contributing +S to the total.
- The element that wraps from position n-1 to position 0 has its multiplier decreased by n (from n-1 to 0), so we subtract n times that element.

Iterating this recurrence from F(0) gives all F(k) values in linear time, allowing us to track the maximum.

The formula works even when values are negative (we simply take the global maximum among all rotations).

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1)
"""
